98. porro, in the next place.— fecundior, more remunerativa

99. perit. . . olei plus, on this more time arrd more oil are wasted,· cf. the proverbial expression et ope· ram et oleum perdere. Work by. lamplight was done by the Ro- mans generally in the morning rather than in the evening. Schools opened before sunrise; cf. vss. 222-227. Pliny (Ep. 111. 5. 8 and 9) states that Vespasian began work before daybreak, and that his uncle, the elder Pliny, commenced his day’s work, in winter, never later than two in the morning, and often earlier. . Phrases like haec scripsi ante lucem (Q. sr. 11. 3) are not uncom- mon in Cicero; cf. Hor. Ep. 11. r. 112 prius orto sole calamum posco.

100. modo, limr't. — millesima pagina surgit: ie. the work grows till the thousandth page is reached. ⁸

102. operum lex: ie. the na- ture of historical composition3 every event must be fully treated.

104. acta: ie. the acta diurna, a daily official record of events of interest, such as births, deaths,

funerals, fires, edicts of magis· trates, decrees of the senate, and reports of trials. The publication of the acta began with Julius Caesar in 59 ac. They were posted in a public place, and copies were distributed by private enterprise. Some idea of their contents may be obtained from a‘ parody read by the actuarius at the supper of Trimalchio, Petr. 53.
